A MALE passenger was declared dead after two trains collided yesterday afternoon. The trains were travelling between Kaalfontein and Tembisa train stations in Ekurhuleni.Apparently the trains, both carrying passengers, were travelling in opposite directions when they collided head-on and about 242 commuters were injured.Ekurhuleni Emergency Services spokesman William Tladi said they were dealing with the situation.&ldquo;The incident took place between Kaalfontein and Kempton Park, when two trains travelling in the same lane collided. Emergency services acted urgently to attend to the incident.&rdquo; Tladi said commuters suffered serious injuries and were transported to various hospitals. Tladi said the injured were taken to Far East Rand Hospital, Tambo Memorial Hospital and Tembisa Hospital. One person was declared dead at the scene.Apparently, the dead passenger was found trapped in the wreckage.Netcare 911&rsquo;s Chris Botha said it will probably take more than a day to clear the scene. &ldquo;Paramedics arrived at the scene and after treating the injured, found one man had tragically died before their arrival.&ldquo;Others had injuries ranging from serious to minor. Paramedics stabilised the injured before they were transported to hospitals.&rdquo;Ekurhuleni mayor Mzwandile Masina expressed his condolences to the family and friends of the man who died during the collision.&ldquo;Our hearts go out to the dead man&rsquo;s family and friends. We also wish the hundreds of people who were injured a speedy recovery. &ldquo;This is a sad incident indeed. &ldquo;We are saddened and disturbed by the loss of life and the accident. Hopefully, investigations will explain what happened and ensure that such incidents are avoided,&rdquo; said Masina.